\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 You are a coding agent whose expertise is turning PRDs into a working app\
\
i will give you a product vision with a set of requirements. you will skillfully generate a prototype with codebase I can download and push into production.\
\
Product Vision\
User Story	User Need\
I am a keen reader who quickly forgets what I read, unless it gets actively recalled by rewriting the key points	I need a tool that helps me rewrite and recall key points from what I read\
I rarely have time to sit down and rewrite the key points on a piece of paper / phone / laptop after each reading session; it\'92s just too time consuming	I need a way to recap what I read without spending too much additional time on top of the reading itself\
Even if I did rewrite, each different book or chapter summaries would be scattered across various sources, making it difficult to access and recall in the future	I need to consolidate my key points and summaries into a single, easily-accessible database\
 \
Based on the user stories and needs, I want to build:\
- A mobile iOS app that allows me to write and recall reading key points (address user need #1)\
- The app allows me to record a voice note and translate it into chunks of information and facts about the book (address user need #2)\
- Each translation will be stored in a neat, modular fashion categorized by the book title in a single app (address user need #3)\
\
\
Detailed Requirements\
\
1. User flow\
    1. In this MVP phase, there will be no registration / log in flow. instead the data would be stored locally on each device without options to switch between different accounts\
    2. When i open the app, the landing page would show me a list of book titles I\'92ve registered and wrote notes of. These cards would be clickable and open up summarized information about the book. Each card in the landing page would be sorted from top to bottom based on the recently edited, and would show the following info\
        1. book title\
        2. last edited date & time\
        3. snapshot/summarized text of last note added in\
    3. At the top right corner of the landing page, there would we an \'93add\'94 button to create a new book title\
        1. after clicking this button, a pop up will ask me to write the book title and submit\
        2. after submit, i will be brought into a clean new page with two note-writing options, each having its own separate tab inside the page:\
            1. voice mode\
            2. type mode\
\
2. Voice vs Type mode\
    1. Voice mode is meant for recording medium-to-long facts, stories, and insights from a single reading session of a book. The form of input is restricted to voice recording.\
        1. when i enter the voice mode tab within the book page, there will be cards showing previously recorded voice notes in the form of a text\
        2. I can create a new voice entry by clicking a mic button on the bottom of the page, which will authorize the microphone of my phone (iOS) and record whatever entries I make.\
        3. Once i\'92ve done talking, i can press done and the app will transcribe my voice into raw text, which will then offer 2 options\
            1. i can edit the text to refine what i just said, OR,\
            2. i can skip editing and press \'93summarize with AI\'94 which will call a locally installed LLM (or call a commercial API, tradeoffs to be discussed) and summarize my raw text into concise piece of story - maintaining my initial input information but eliminating noise, redundant words, while also refining the logic behind my text\
        4. this will produce 1 voice entry id within the book id. and each voice entry id will keep\
            1. raw text transcribed from my voice note\
            2. shorter, summarized text after AI processing\
        5. there will be no need to keep the voice recording mp3 file, only need text\
    2. Type mode is meant for noting down short-form text which describes new or interesting vocabularies, places, phrases, idioms, historical events I learned from the book for future reference and research. the form of input here is directly from user typing.\
        1. when i enter the type mode tab within the book page, there will be cards showing previously inputted text\
        2. one type entry id is restricted to max 10 words\
        3. i can create a new type entry by clicking an \'93add\'94 button on the bottom of the page, which will summon a pop up where i can input the text\
        4. as i type the text, there will be a dropdown list showing potential word/phrase matches just like when i type something on google search, it will recommend the most relevant topic (logic for this to be discussed, if too complicated we can skip this)\
        5. after typing, i can submit the text and it will create a new type entry id under the book id\
        6. each type entry id has a google icon, which when clicked will automatically redirect to a default browser and search the text into google.com\
\
3. UI/UX guidance\
    1. make the app simple but nice to look at (choose a nice color pallette)\
    2. minimize the number of clicks for each interaction flow\
    3. offer light vs dark mode toggle at the home screen / landing page\
\
Next actions for you\
- before writing code for the prototype app, challenge me on my design decisions and give me options on the effort / complexity on the above requirements. for example:\
    - is it better to build a web app version first instead of an iOS mobile app?\
    - for the voice mode, how hard is it to embed an LLM into the logic? which is better, installing a locally running LLM (free and open source) or calling an API? if the former, what options do we have for the local LLM model?\
    - logistics-wise, how do I test the prototype before actually migrating it into a proper web app / mobile app? and how to migrate it eventually into a production-ready app?}